{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17596415","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17596415"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:12:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:12:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15407"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15407","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15407"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.85,0,0,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8098"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69795"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8098","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8098"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15407"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55251"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8127"},{"type":"tags","id":"8137"},{"type":"tags","id":"9507"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19646"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19648"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69795","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69795"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA colorectal polyp is sent to the pathology laboratory for examination. Microscopy reveals the polyp is attached to the colonic mucosa by a stalk. The architectural pattern shows 40% villous and 60% tubular components.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes this colorectal polyp?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Sessile tubulovillous adenoma","Pedunculated tubulovillous adenoma","Sessile villous adenoma","Pedunculated villous adenoma","Pedunculated tubular adenoma"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis polyp is a \u003Cstrong\u003Epedunculated tubulovillous adenoma\u003C/strong\u003E. The presence of a stalk defines it as pedunculated rather than \u003Cstrong\u003Esessile\u003C/strong\u003E. The mixed architecture with 40% villous components places it in the tubulovillous category (25-75% villous), rather than purely \u003Cstrong\u003Evillous\u003C/strong\u003E (\u003E75% villous) or purely \u003Cstrong\u003Etubular\u003C/strong\u003E (\u003C25% villous).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EColorectal adenomas are classified by two key features:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EGrowth pattern: pedunculated (on a stalk) vs sessile (flat-based)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EHistological architecture: tubular, villous, or mixed (tubulovillous)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe proportion of villous architecture correlates with malignant potential:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003ETubular adenomas - lowest risk\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ETubulovillous adenomas - intermediate risk\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EVillous adenomas - highest risk\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Colorectal adenomas are classified as tubular (\u003C25% villous), tubulovillous (25-75% villous), or villous (\u003E75% villous) based on their histological architecture.","Pedunculated polyps are attached to the mucosa by a stalk, while sessile polyps are flat or slightly elevated without a stalk.","The risk of malignant transformation increases with villous architecture, with villous adenomas having the highest risk."],"references":["Hossain MS, Karuniawati H, Jairoun AA, Urbi Z, Ooi J, John A, Lim YC, Kibria KMK, Mohiuddin AKM, Ming LC, Goh KW, Hadi MA. Colorectal Cancer: A Review of Carcinogenesis, Global Epidemiology, Current Challenges, Risk Factors, Preventive and Treatment Strategies. Cancers (Basel). 2022 Mar 29;14(7):1732. doi: 10.3390/cancers14071732. PMID: 35406504; PMCID: PMC8996939","Duan B, Zhao Y, Bai J, et al. Colorectal Cancer: An Overview. In: Morgado-Diaz JA, editor. Gastrointestinal Cancers [Internet]. Brisbane (AU): Exon Publications; 2022 Sep 30. Chapter 1. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK586003/ doi: 10.36255/exon-publications-gastrointestinal-cancers-colorectal-cancer","Lewandowska A, Rudzki G, Lewandowski T, Stryjkowska-G\u00f3ra A, Rudzki S. Risk Factors for the Diagnosis of Colorectal Cancer. Cancer Control. 2022 Jan-Dec;29:10732748211056692. doi: 10.1177/10732748211056692. PMID: 35000418; PMCID: PMC8753079","Sawicki T, Ruszkowska M, Danielewicz A, Nied\u017awiedzka E, Ar\u0142ukowicz T, Przyby\u0142owicz KE. A Review of Colorectal Cancer in Terms of Epidemiology, Risk Factors, Development, Symptoms and Diagnosis. Cancers (Basel). 2021 Apr 22;13(9):2025. doi: 10.3390/cancers13092025. PMID: 33922197; PMCID: PMC8122718","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55251"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15407"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55251","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55251"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-12T19:46:27+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-12T19:47:54+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8098"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69795"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attribute